{"title_page": "Mark Hobson", "text_new": "{{for|the British boxer|Mark Hobson (boxer)}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name               =Mark Richard Hobson\n| image              =Mark Hobson.png\n| image_size         =150px\n| nationality        =British\n| birth_date         ={{Birth date and age|1969|09|02|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        =[[Wakefield]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]]\n| conviction            = [[Grievous bodily harm|Wounding with intent to cause grievous bodily harm]] and [[Bail|Failing to comply with bail conditions]] (June 2003)<br>[[Breach of the peace]] (July 2003)<br>[[Theft]] and [[Deception (criminal law)|Deception]] (February 2004)<br>[[Murder]] - four counts (May 2005)\n| conviction_penalty         = 100 hours [[Community Service]] and 2 years [[Probation]]<br>Fined [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]50<br>50 hours Community Service<br>[[Life imprisonment]] (4 terms) with a [[whole life tariff]]\n| conviction_status  =Imprisoned\n}}\n'''Mark Richard Hobson''' (born 2 September 1969) is a British [[spree killer]] who killed four people in [[North Yorkshire]], [[England]] in July 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Killer faces families as he admits deaths of four people|first1=Nigel|last1=Bunyan|first2=Paul|last2=Stokes|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=1 March 2005|page=11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Downfall of a desperado fuelled by alcohol|date=23 July 2004|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1467647/Downfall-of-a-desperado-fuelled-by-alcohol.html|accessdate=15 July 2011}}</ref> He was arrested after an eight-day nationwide manhunt involving more than 500 police officers and 12 police forces, during which time he was Britain's \"most wanted man\".<ref>{{Cite news|title=Britain's most wanted captured at last|first=Ian|last=Herbert|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|location=Belfast|date=26 July 2004|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Tragic pair shared life and death|work=[[Yorkshire Post]]|location=Leeds|date=19 April 2005|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=We've got him, we've got him|date=26 July 2004|work=[[Yorkshire Post]]|location=Leeds|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/around-yorkshire/local-stories/we_ve_got_him_we_ve_got_him_1_2547089|accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Hunt ends for most wanted man|first1=Helen|last1=Carter|first2=Martin|last2=Wainwright|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|date=26 July 2004|page=1}}</ref>\n\nPolice discovered notes written by Hobson that showed the murders were pre-meditated and well-planned, including a 'to-do' note detailing how he planned to lure his girlfriend's twin sister to his flat and a shopping list for \"big bin liners,\" tape, tie-wraps, fly spray and air freshener.<ref name=keely /> Against his girlfriend's sister's name he had written \"use and abuse at will.\"<ref name=yorkshirepost /> The list of planned victims also included his girlfriend's parents and the parents of his ex-wife.<ref name=\"keely\">{{Cite news|title=Blade brute had hit-list... and wanted to wipe out the twins' entire family|last=Keely|first=Alistair|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|location=Glasgow|date=19 April 2005|pages=8\u20139}}</ref>\n\nHobson was tried for the murders in April 2005. Pleading guilty, he was sentenced to four terms of [[life imprisonment]] with a recommendation that he should [[Whole life tariff|never be released]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Whole life tariffs: prisoners who will die behind bars|first=Tom|last=Rowley|date=16 July 2010|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/7894459/Whole-life-tariffs-prisoners-who-will-die-behind-bars.html|accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref> This was one of the first times that such a recommendation had been made for someone who had admitted their crime at the first opportunity.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Four-times killer will never be released from jail|last=Stokes|first=Paul|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=28 May 2005|page=10}}</ref> He is currently incarcerated at [[Wakefield Prison]], West Yorkshire.\n\n==Early life==\nHobson was born at Manygates Maternity Hospital in [[Wakefield]] on 2 September 1969.<ref name=\"yorkshirepost2\">{{Cite news|title='Sweet, innocent face' of Hobson the boy recalled|date=23 July 2004|work=[[Yorkshire Post]]|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/around-yorkshire/local-stories/sweet_innocent_face_of_hobson_the_boy_recalled_1_2547039|accessdate=14 July 2011}}</ref> The first family home was in Norton Street, Wakefield, where Hobson grew up with his parents Peter and Sandra and his two sisters, Melanie and Leslie. They then moved to Woodhouse Road, Eastmoor. His father was a coal miner who had started his career at Walton colliery in 1958 and later become deputy and over-manager at the city's Park Hill colliery until its closure in 1982.<ref name=\"spiral\">{{Cite news|title=Downward spiral into violence and murder|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/around-yorkshire/local-stories/downward_spiral_into_violence_and_murder_1_2366469|first1=Kate|last1=O'Hara|first2=Mark|last2=Branagan|work=[[Yorkshire Post]]|location=Leeds|date=19 April 2005|page=1}}</ref> The family then moved to the [[Selby]] area where Peter Hobson took work at a local coalfield. Hobson's mother worked as a machinist. Hobson's childhood was described by his contemporaries as \"happy and stable.\"<ref name=spiral /> He attended Heath View Primary School in Eastmoor, Wakefield, Staynor High School and Brayton High School, Selby. One of Hobson's teachers recalled him as \"very well behaved... so average and ordinary that he was almost anonymous.\"<ref name=spiral />\n\n==Later life==\nIn 1991 Hobson moved in with his childhood sweetheart and her two children from another relationship. They married in 1993, after the birth of their daughter. Hobson worked at [[Drax power station]] and as a landscape gardener. His wife described him as the \"perfect husband.\"<ref name=\"bunyan2\">{{Cite news|title=Small town loser who consumed so much pot and booze he was a zombie|first1=Nigel|last1=Bunyan|first2=Paul|last2=Stokes|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=19 April 2005|page=4}}</ref> In 1998 Hobson [[Bouncer (doorman)#United Kingdom|registered as a nightclub doorman]] and began working at \"Kans\" nightclub in Market Place, Selby.<ref name=spiral /> On New Year's Day 1999, he walked out on his family without giving a reason and began using [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] and drinking heavily.<ref name=craven /> His wife said: \"There was no one else involved, he just didn't want married life any more. It was bizarre. I couldn't believe it. He turned to pot and drinking heavily. He never drank when we were married but now he got out of his face. He became like a zombie... His life just went completely off the rails.\"<ref name=bunyan2 />\n\n==Murders==\n===Claire Sanderson===\nDuring the evening of 10 July 2004, he killed his girlfriend Claire Sanderson, 27, in the flat they shared on Millfield Drive, [[Camblesforth]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=House where sisters' bodies were found is put up for sale|work=[[Yorkshire Post]]|location=Leeds|date=16 Nov 2004|page=1}}</ref> She was struck on the head seventeen times with a hammer and strangled, after which Hobson wrapped her body in binbags.<ref name=\"norfolk\">{{Cite news|title=Horrific trail of deadly lover|last=Norfolk|first=Andrew|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=19 April 2005|page=3}}</ref><ref name=\"brooke\">{{Cite news|title=Why Was Monster Free To Kill?|last=Brooke|first=Chris|work=[[Daily Mail]]|location=London|date=19 April 2005|page=10}}</ref> A plastic bag had also been placed over her head. Subsequent forensic analysis determined that an area of the flat had been cleaned with bleach but Claire had been first attacked in the living room and then taken into the bathroom. There was no evidence of recent sexual activity.<ref name=western />\n\n===Diane Sanderson===\nOn 17 July, he telephoned Sanderson's twin sister Diane and told her Claire was ill with [[Infectious mononucleosis|glandular fever]] and wanted her to visit. When Diane arrived at the flat that evening she too was beaten with a hammer after being tortured with a disposable razor and scissors and sexually assaulted.<ref name=norfolk /><ref name=brooke /> She had been \"[[Hogtie bondage|hogtied]]\" and her left nipple was completely bitten off.<ref name=\"yorkshirepost\">{{Cite news|title=Secret hit list of four-time murderer Scribbled notes show he planned to claim more victims|date=19 April 2005|work=[[Yorkshire Post]]|location=Leeds|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/around-yorkshire/local-stories/secret_hit_list_of_four_time_murderer_scribbled_notes_show_he_planned_to_claim_more_victims_1_2366480|accessdate=14 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"western\">{{Cite news|title=Slaughter of the innocents|work=[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]|location=Cardiff|date=19 April 2005|page=1}}</ref> Police believe Hobson may have eaten it.<ref name=\"craven\">{{Cite news|title=A terrifying hunger for violence, fuelled by cannabis and alcohol|last1=Craven|first1=Nick|last2=Tozer|first2=James|work=[[Daily Mail]]|location=London|date=19 April 2005|page=10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Killer of twins and elderly couple may have been planning more murders|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|location=Cork|date=19 April 2005}}</ref> The cause of her death was determined to be strangulation.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Binman went on murder spree because he 'chose wrong twin as his girlfriend'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1488156/Binman-went-on-murder-spree-because-he-chose-wrong-twin-as-his-girlfriend.html|accessdate=14 July 2011|last=Stokes|first=Paul|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=19 April 2005|page=4}}</ref> Her head was also covered with a plastic bag and ligatures were found on  her wrists, ankles and neck. Her pubic hair had been shaved and she had been sexually assaulted.<ref name=western />\n\n===James and Joan Britton===\nThe next day, he murdered an elderly couple, James and Joan Britton, at their home in [[Strensall]], [[York]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/north_yorkshire/4455709.stm | title=Man pleads guilty to four murders| date=2005-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==Arrest and trial==\nHobson was arrested at a petrol station on 25 July 2004, in the village of Shipton-by-Beningbrough, near [[York]], following a nationwide manhunt.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/north_yorkshire/3909539.stm Man hunted for four murders] [[BBC News]], 20 July 2004</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1468816/Hobson-is-remanded-over-double-murders.html Hobson is remanded over double murders] Telegraph, 6 August 2004</ref> At his subsequent trial in April 2005, Hobson admitted all four murders.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/crime/article/0,2763,1462475,00.html Man pleads guilty to four murders] [[The Guardian]], 18 April 2005</ref> He was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] on 27 May 2005 with a recommendation that he should never be released.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/north_yorkshire/4586617.stm Murderer must spend life in jail] [[BBC News]], 27 May 2005</ref>\n\nThe court was also told that Hobson had stabbed a love rival five times in the chest in a daylight attack in front of shoppers in [[Selby]] in 2002, leaving the victim with a punctured lung. Hobson had admitted grievous bodily harm and avoided a prison sentence, instead receiving a community punishment order. This lenient sentence came under much criticism in the light of Hobson's later offending.\n\n==Appeal==\nHobson lodged an appeal to have a lower minimum sentence set, claiming that he should have been given a more lenient sentence because he had admitted all four murders at the earliest opportunity. He also claimed that no other murderer who admitted their crimes at the first opportunity had ever been recommended for lifelong imprisonment. This was not true, as a similar recommendation had been imposed on child killers [[Timothy Morss]] and [[Brett Tyler]] in 1996 even though they had admitted their crimes at the earliest opportunity.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/personal-view/3580547/Silence-as-the-terrible-truth-is-revealed.html Silence as the terrible truth is revealed] Telegraph, 18 August 2002</ref>\n\nThe appeal was turned down by the [[Court of Appeal]] when [[Nicholas Phillips, Baron Phillips of Worth Matravers|Lord Phillips]] agreed with the trial judge's recommendation, saying that in his opinion, Hobson should never be released, regardless of a guilty plea, since the murders had been so horrific.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/north_yorkshire/4484502.stm Killer Hobson loses tariff appeal] [[BBC News]], 30 November 2005</ref>\n\n==Imprisonment==\nShortly before this court case, Hobson was placed into solitary confinement for three months after attacking [[Ian Huntley]] (a former school caretaker convicted of [[Soham Murders|murdering two girls]] at a [[Cambridgeshire]] school), and scalding him with a bucket of boiling water. A prison service spokesman said that, due to the nature of high-security prisoners, \"it's impossible to prevent incidents of this nature occasionally happening.\"\n\nIn January 2006, letters were released from [[Wakefield Prison]] where Hobson blamed alcohol for his killing spree. It had been revealed at Hobson's trial that he was an [[Alcoholism|alcoholic]] who regularly drank as many as 20 pints a day, and also used other drugs regularly.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1488155/Small-town-loser-who-consumed-so-much-pot-and-booze-he-was-a-zombie.html Small town loser who consumed so much pot and booze he was a zombie] Telegraph, 19 April 2005</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hobson, Mark}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Wakefield]]\n[[Category:English people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by England and Wales]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by England and Wales]]\n[[Category:English prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n[[Category:British spree killers]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Yorkshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the British boxer|Mark Hobson (boxer)}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name               =Mark Richard Hobson\n| image              =Mark Hobson.png\n| image_size         =150px\n| nationality        =British\n| birth_date         ={{Birth date and age|1969|09|02|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        =[[Wakefield]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]]\n| conviction            = [[Grievous bodily harm|Wounding with intent to cause grievous bodily harm]] and [[Bail|Failing to comply with bail conditions]] (June 2003)<br>[[Breach of the peace]] (July 2003)<br>[[Theft]] and [[Deception (criminal law)|Deception]] (February 2004)<br>[[Murder]] - four counts (May 2005)\n| conviction_penalty         = 100 hours [[Community Service]] and 2 years [[Probation]]<br>Fined [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]50<br>50 hours Community Service<br>[[Life imprisonment]] (4 terms) with a [[whole life tariff]]\n| conviction_status  =Imprisoned\n}}\n'''Mark Richard Hobson''' (born 2 September 1969) is a British [[spree killer]] who killed four people in [[North Yorkshire]], [[England]] in July 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Killer faces families as he admits deaths of four people|first1=Nigel|last1=Bunyan|first2=Paul|last2=Stokes|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=1 March 2005|page=11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Downfall of a desperado fuelled by alcohol|date=23 July 2004|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1467647/Downfall-of-a-desperado-fuelled-by-alcohol.html|accessdate=15 July 2011}}</ref> He was arrested after an eight-day nationwide manhunt involving more than 500 police officers and 12 police forces, during which time he was Britain's \"most wanted man\".<ref>{{Cite news|title=Britain's most wanted captured at last|first=Ian|last=Herbert|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|location=Belfast|date=26 July 2004|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Tragic pair shared life and death|work=[[Yorkshire Post]]|location=Leeds|date=19 April 2005|page=1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=We've got him, we've got him|date=26 July 2004|work=[[Yorkshire Post]]|location=Leeds|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/around-yorkshire/local-stories/we_ve_got_him_we_ve_got_him_1_2547089|accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Hunt ends for most wanted man|first1=Helen|last1=Carter|first2=Martin|last2=Wainwright|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|date=26 July 2004|page=1}}</ref>\n\nPolice discovered notes written by Hobson that showed the murders were pre-meditated and well-planned, including a 'to-do' note detailing how he planned to lure his girlfriend's twin sister to his flat and a shopping list for \"big bin liners,\" tape, tie-wraps, fly spray and air freshener.<ref name=keely /> Against his girlfriend's sister's name he had written \"use and abuse at will.\"<ref name=yorkshirepost /> The list of planned victims also included his girlfriend's parents and the parents of his ex-wife.<ref name=\"keely\">{{Cite news|title=Blade brute had hit-list... and wanted to wipe out the twins' entire family|last=Keely|first=Alistair|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|location=Glasgow|date=19 April 2005|pages=8\u20139}}</ref>\n\nHobson was tried for the murders in April 2005. Pleading guilty, he was sentenced to four terms of [[life imprisonment]] with a recommendation that he should [[Whole life tariff|never be released]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Whole life tariffs: prisoners who will die behind bars|first=Tom|last=Rowley|date=16 July 2010|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=London|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/7894459/Whole-life-tariffs-prisoners-who-will-die-behind-bars.html|accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref> This was one of the first times that such a recommendation had been made for someone who had admitted their crime at the first opportunity.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Four-times killer will never be released from jail|last=Stokes|first=Paul|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=28 May 2005|page=10}}</ref> He is currently incarcerated at [[Wakefield Prison]], West Yorkshire.\n\n==Early life==\nHobson was born at Manygates Maternity Hospital in [[Wakefield]] on 2 September 1969.<ref name=\"yorkshirepost2\">{{Cite news|title='Sweet, innocent face' of Hobson the boy recalled|date=23 July 2004|work=[[Yorkshire Post]]|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/around-yorkshire/local-stories/sweet_innocent_face_of_hobson_the_boy_recalled_1_2547039|accessdate=14 July 2011}}</ref> The first family home was located at Norton Street, Wakefield, where Hobson grew up with his parents Peter and Sandra and his two sisters, Melanie and Leslie. They then moved to Woodhouse Road, Eastmoor. His father was a coal miner who had started his career at Walton colliery in 1958 and later become deputy and over-manager at the city's Park Hill colliery until its closure in 1982.<ref name=\"spiral\">{{Cite news|title=Downward spiral into violence and murder|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/around-yorkshire/local-stories/downward_spiral_into_violence_and_murder_1_2366469|first1=Kate|last1=O'Hara|first2=Mark|last2=Branagan|work=[[Yorkshire Post]]|location=Leeds|date=19 April 2005|page=1}}</ref> The family then moved to the [[Selby]] area where Peter Hobson took work at a local coalfield. Hobson's mother worked as a machinist. Hobson's childhood was described by his contemporaries as \"happy and stable.\"<ref name=spiral /> He attended Heath View Primary School in Eastmoor, Wakefield, Staynor High School and Brayton High School, Selby. One of Hobson's teachers recalled him as \"very well behaved... so average and ordinary that he was almost anonymous.\"<ref name=spiral />\n\n==Later life==\nIn 1991 Hobson moved in with his childhood sweetheart and her two children from another relationship. They married in 1993, after the birth of their daughter. Hobson worked at [[Drax power station]] and as a landscape gardener. His wife described him as the \"perfect husband.\"<ref name=\"bunyan2\">{{Cite news|title=Small town loser who consumed so much pot and booze he was a zombie|first1=Nigel|last1=Bunyan|first2=Paul|last2=Stokes|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=19 April 2005|page=4}}</ref> In 1998 Hobson [[Bouncer (doorman)#United Kingdom|registered as a nightclub doorman]] and began working at \"Kans\" nightclub in Market Place, Selby.<ref name=spiral /> On New Year's Day 1999, he walked out on his family without giving a reason and began using [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] and drinking heavily.<ref name=craven /> His wife said: \"There was no one else involved, he just didn't want married life any more. It was bizarre. I couldn't believe it. He turned to pot and drinking heavily. He never drank when we were married but now he got out of his face. He became like a zombie... His life just went completely off the rails.\"<ref name=bunyan2 />\n\n==Murders==\n===Claire Sanderson===\nDuring the evening of 10 July 2004, he killed his girlfriend Claire Sanderson, 27, in the flat they shared on Millfield Drive, [[Camblesforth]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=House where sisters' bodies were found is put up for sale|work=[[Yorkshire Post]]|location=Leeds|date=16 Nov 2004|page=1}}</ref> She was struck on the head seventeen times with a hammer and strangled, after which Hobson wrapped her body in binbags.<ref name=\"norfolk\">{{Cite news|title=Horrific trail of deadly lover|last=Norfolk|first=Andrew|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=19 April 2005|page=3}}</ref><ref name=\"brooke\">{{Cite news|title=Why Was Monster Free To Kill?|last=Brooke|first=Chris|work=[[Daily Mail]]|location=London|